hands_on_practices.problem:
A blood vessel segment is modeled as a straight, rigid, cylindrical tube of radius $R=2\,\text{mm}$ carrying steady, incompressible, laminar flow of a Newtonian fluid representing blood plasma with dynamic viscosity $\mu=3\,\text{centipoise}$ (where $1\,\text{centipoise} = 10^{-3}\,\text{pascal}\cdot\text{second}$). The volumetric flow rate is $Q=10\,\text{milliliter}/\text{second}$ (where $1\,\text{milliliter} = 10^{-6}\,\text{meter}^{3}$). Assume the no-slip boundary condition at the vessel wall and the classical parabolic velocity profile of laminar flow in a cylinder. The wall shear rate is defined as the magnitude of the radial derivative of the axial velocity profile evaluated at the wall, and the wall shear stress is defined as the product of the dynamic viscosity and the wall shear rate.

Starting only from fundamental fluid-mechanical facts applicable to steady, laminar flow in a cylindrical tube—namely, that the axial velocity profile is parabolic, that the volumetric flow rate equals the area integral of the velocity, and that the wall shear rate equals the wall gradient of the velocity—derive the wall shear rate in terms of $Q$ and $R$, then compute its numerical value. Next, compute the wall shear stress from the wall shear rate and the given viscosity. Finally, to connect hemodynamics to thrombus morphology, use the following well-tested pathological heuristic: high-shear environments (shear rate $\dot{\gamma} \geq \gamma^{\ast}$ with $\gamma^{\ast}=500\,\text{s}^{-1}$) favor platelet-rich (white) thrombi, while low-shear environments (shear rate $\dot{\gamma} < \gamma^{\ast}$) favor fibrin- and erythrocyte-rich (red) thrombi. Define a composition index $C$ by
$$
C=\begin{cases}
1 & \text{if } \dot{\gamma} \geq \gamma^{\ast} \\
0 & \text{if } \dot{\gamma} < \gamma^{\ast}
\end{cases}
$$
where $C=1$ denotes platelet-rich and $C=0$ denotes fibrin/erythrocyte-rich.

Express the wall shear rate in $\text{s}^{-1}$ and the wall shear stress in $\text{pascal}$, and round both to four significant figures. Provide your final answer as a row matrix containing three entries in the order $\dot{\gamma}$, $\tau_{w}$, $C$.
